Immediately following the removal of impulsivities, we want to obtain the linear components of the acceleration to focus solely on the motion aspects of the signal. Calculating linear acceleraton allows us to ignore the effects of gravity and focus on changes in velocity due to body movement. With proper linear accelerometry, we enhance our ability to recognize the underlying activity and possibly derive insights about the heart rate over time.
Since linear accelerometery provides essential information about motion, it forms a crucial part of our overall analysis process.
Now that we have cleaned and extracted linear accelerometric values, we proceed to examine the dominant spectral characteristics of the resulting signal.
Identifying the most significant frequency components will give us clues about the activity taking place and enable us to draw conclusions about the subject's actions.
Furthermore, once we have determined the dominant activity, it opens up possibilities for investigating indirect measures of heart rate, suchas stride duration or cadence.
